EMEA Content Statistical Model Refresh Pipeline
Data Portfolio · Project 4
Author: Jashwanth Anand Shankar — MSc Business Analytics, Warwick Business School
Contact: jashwanth240298@gmail.com · linkedin.com/in/jash24298
---
The Problem This Solves
In a production finance analytics environment, source data is updated regularly —
new productions are added, budget figures are corrected, ratings are revised.
Before this pipeline: Every update required a manual re-analysis cycle:
re-load the data, re-clean it, re-run all statistical models, re-generate all reports.
This took approximately 4 hours per refresh cycle and required senior analyst time.
After this pipeline: A single command detects whether the data has changed
and, if so, automatically runs the full pipeline end-to-end — in under 2 minutes.
```bash
python emea_stat_refresh.py --source emea_content_data.csv
```
---
What the Pipeline Does
```
Source CSV
    │
    ├─► 1. Change Detection      MD5 hash comparison — only runs if data changed
    │
    ├─► 2. Ingestion & Validation  Schema check, value range validation, quality flags
    │
    ├─► 3. Cleaning & Imputation   Country-year median imputation for missing budgets
    │
    ├─► 4. Statistical Models      CAGR · Linear trend regression · Genre scoring · YoY matrix
    │
    └─► 5. Output Generation       CSVs + plain-text summary + JSON audit log
```
---
Statistical Models Computed
Model	Method	Business use
Market summary	Group aggregation	Spend oversight ranking
CAGR by market	Compound growth formula	Identify fastest-growing markets
Trend regression	Scipy linregress (OLS)	Detect stable vs volatile output trends
Genre performance	Rating × log(audience)	Content investment prioritisation
YoY growth matrix	Pandas pct_change + pivot	Year-on-year reporting for PR/GR teams
---
Installation
```bash
pip install -r requirements.txt
```
---
Usage
```bash
# Standard run — only refreshes if data has changed
python emea_stat_refresh.py --source emea_content_data.csv

# Force re-run regardless of change detection
python emea_stat_refresh.py --source emea_content_data.csv --force

# Custom output directory
python emea_stat_refresh.py --source emea_content_data.csv --output /reports/emea/
```
---
Output Files
After each successful run, the following are written to the output directory:
File	Description
`market_summary.csv`	Spend, productions, rating per EMEA market
`cagr_by_market.csv`	Compound annual growth rate per market
`trend_regression.csv`	OLS slope, R², p-value per market
`genre_performance.csv`	Composite performance score per genre
`yoy_growth_matrix.csv`	Year-on-year % change, all markets × all years
`refresh_summary.txt`	Plain-English summary for non-technical stakeholders
`refresh_log.json`	Audit trail: timestamp, source hash, output files
---
Onboarding a New Team Member
Clone/download this repository
Run `pip install -r requirements.txt`
Place your source CSV in the project directory
Run the pipeline with `python emea_stat_refresh.py --source <your_file.csv>`
Find all outputs in the `outputs/` folder
Read `outputs/refresh_summary.txt` for a plain-English interpretation
No manual steps. No configuration files to edit. No analyst hand-holding required.
---
Project Background
This script is a simplified, anonymised recreation of an automation built at
Stellantis to eliminate manual statistical re-analysis when plant-side design
or manufacturing process data was updated. The original reduced a 4-hour
manual cycle to a fully automated sub-2-minute pipeline and was used to
onboard 5 new team members without requiring analyst support.
